				<div class="postbody">
				I don't like Bush (but hot damn .. NASA .. it's about time!), and I don't think the war in Iraq was necessary to protect America.
<br />

<br />
But I do agree that once the troops are mobilized, it's too late to protest. I'm not going to say that protesting a war is unpatriotic or traitorious, but I will say it's certainly disrespectful. No matter how thoroughly disgusting the politics of the matter may be, our soldiers do what we ask of them. They don't question whether it's the right thing to do, they just do it. And when they get back, I don't care if they were POWs or if they killed an entire platoon with a half-empty pistol or if they just sat at a comfortable desk in an air-conditioned modular building. They serve, they're heroes. 
<br />

<br />
It's not about being sheep. It's about showing some respect to the men and women who put their bodies between us and our enemies (real or contrived). If you don't like what our soldiers are asked to do, the time to protest is during those few precious minutes you're alone in the voting booth. (And yes, I've probably watched <span style="font-style: italic">A Few Good Men</span> one too many times. Who can resist Jack in that georgeous white uniform?)
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Son, we live in a world that has walls, and those walls have to be guarded by men with guns. Whose gonna do it? You? You, Lt. Weinburg? I have more responsibility here than you could possibly fathom. You weep for Santiago, and you curse the Marines. You have that luxury. You have the luxury of not knowing what I know. That Santiago's death, while tragic, probably saved lives. And that my existence, while grotesque and incomprehensible to you, saves lives. I know deep down in places you dont talk about at parties, you don't want me on that wall, you <span style="font-style: italic">need</span> me on that wall. We use words like honor, code, loyalty. We use these words as the backbone of a life spent defending something. You use them as a punchline. I have neither the time nor the inclination to explain myself to a man who rises and sleeps under the blanket of the very freedom I provide, then question the manner in which I provide it. I prefer you said thank you, and went on your way, Otherwise, I suggest you pick up a weapon, and stand to post. Either way, I don't give a damn what you think you are entitled to! </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
As an aside, I don't know what the seventeen points were in the WMD discussion, but I do have seventeen rebuttals. North Korea. Singapore. Burma. Cuba. Libya.  Sudan. Tibet. Turkmenistan. Chechnya. Syria. Saudi Arabia. Congo. Eritrea. Laos. Bahrain. Kyrgyz Republic. Maldives. And the list just goes on and on. One thing our planet has no shortage of is people who use their power to control others.<br />
