			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Dear Mr. Bigger Black Sheep,  
<br />

<br />
First of all, I'm glad you're actually starting to question some of the leadership decisions of your country.  But after reading your "16 Reasons why the US Invaded Iraq", I am quite dissapointed.
<br />

<br />
You see, it seems as if you're once again a product of manipulation of the undisputed champion of Americans:  George Bush.  A lot of your reasons are based on a percieved 'threat', not on whether or not it merits a full out declaration of war on a country.  And, well, that is pretty weak.
<br />

<br />
Before I begin, I'll assume all of your points can be properly referenced for the sake of debating purposes.
<br />

<br />
Reasons 1,2,3 and 4 come in the light of the widely acclaimed imposing new threat: terrorism.  Mass hysteria from 9/11 prompted many Americans to feel as if they should make someone pay for the act that al-Qaeda (sp?) did in New York.  These four reasons clearly show that you, and many others whom believe that this motivation is a clear basis for declaring war on Iraq, are still suffering this tragic and unwelcome event and decided to take it out on Iraq because, unfortunately, there has still yet to be a complete conclusion in the event with the capture of Bin Laden, etc.  And, correct me if I am wrong (I am not a Law student like most of you think you are),  but are these reasons not pure speculation and hearsay?  They, especially the letter, establish how Iraq disliked America... but they do not prove how they were an 'immediate threat to every citizen of America'.  Weak reasoning, definitely can be seen how easy  it can be manipulated to influence the general public, but I still am hoping for a better rationale for invading Iraq.
<br />

<br />
Reason 5.  Wow, why don't you flex your muscles a little more and point towards the closest beach?  Impress me, you did!  I am glad to know your army exists in Iraq. And that it has been there for a while.. but, does that give it a valid reason for invading the country?  Umm.. no?  Gives a reason for maintaining peace, but not invading..?
<br />

<br />
How can I explain 6 and 14 so that you can see it from a Non-American point of view?  Or, is it even worth trying?  The point is, your excuse pretty much sums up how Americans use the 'brute force method' of making sure everyone is peaceful with them and treats them the best.  Imagine a bully scenario at school in which the bully demands the utmost respect from all of his 'minions'.  Kind of sad.   Now, instead of Bush manipulating the many sheep of America, your country aims to manipulate the countries in the Middle East?  Oy.  Good luck with that one.  It is not an appropriate reason to take over Iraq in order to show that you are mighty and that people should treat you with respect...
<br />

<br />
7) Jihad this, Jihad that.  I jihad you.  Does that mean you should come and remove me from my country because I am a threat?  Once again, no.  And, you also showed yourself this was a weak reason:  "this was futile due to his amoral and very un-muslim lifestyle".
<br />

<br />
Reason 8, ally with Isreal and how Hussein had control of terrorists in Isreal.  I'll take this as truth, and in doing so, the immediate threat lies in Isreal, not America.  Reasoning for invading Iraq validly?  No.
<br />

<br />
Reason 9 can be quite easily placed under the broad category of reason 6.  It's a weak reason only used to show off your big guns.  Hooray for proving a valid point there once again... not.
<br />

<br />
Reason 10 and 15!  I am impressed!  You actually took yourself out of 'Iraq as a personal threat' and into 'Iraq as a threat to the public in Iraq'.  Congratulations on being selfless for a second there.. and by going against the general theme of your argument.  Oh wait, I just read the final part of the 10th reason and how it affected the general American community. Too bad, almost had the same train of thought there.  Oh, wait, this is just speculation into how one scenario could be modelled in another country like America... it did not actually happen.  I am dissapointed... once again, a poor reason.  Could life go on without doing anything in Iraq?  If Bush is president and keeps manipulating the sheep, he'll make as much effort as possible to make this 'personal and affecting every citizen of America'.
<br />

<br />
Reason 10.5, 11, and 12 can be under one heading:  I, a citizen of America, think that my ways of living life are ideal and that everyone should have the equal opportunity to live the way I do.  Therefore, I should go in and remove a non-immediate threat to impose my way of life on everyone else.  I know best.  Believe me. Plus, if I do this, it serves my future goals in manipulating others.  Valid?  No.
<br />

<br />
The fact that Iran was surrounded completely (reason 13) evades me from being an appropriate reason for invading Iraq.  The quote, "num(b)er 3 out of 4 on the "Axis of Evil" declaration" does seem like a Bush'ism, and maybe you can clarify this one with proper referencing and perhaps another discussion because it does not make any sense...?
<br />

<br />

<br />
Oh, and 16, Brem decided to somewhat clear that one up for me a bit.  Thanks for letting me know!  Still, I'm very confused why the US stepped over the toes of the UN.  The UN represents the views of almost the entire world (unless I am incorrect..?) and the US clearly ignored the requests of the world for more time to verify the validity of invading Iraq.
<br />

<br />
That's where my points come about not invading Iraq:
<br />

<br />
1)  Iraq does not pose a clear and present danger.  He was in Iraq.  Americans were in the US.  Could Iraq come over and directly affect the every citizen in the US?  Oy. Imagine that.  Not likely.. not to a scale that could be as bad at 9/11.  Comon now, you guys have the Amber Alert Terror Warning system used to scare more people into manipulation! I bet that helps!
<br />

<br />
2)  A war would kill soldiers.  People would die.  This was proven, and sadly, many Americans died for a cause that is still trying to be justified.  Wow, that is very depressing.
<br />

<br />
3)  Intelligence was supposed to link Iraq to an immediate threat.  How did this work out again...?  Sigh.
<br />

<br />
4)  The cost of such a war.  Oy, I'd hate to see the budget on that bill.  You guys are definitely going to be in debt.  Hope it was worth it.  Oh, and did I mention people died..?
<br />

<br />
5)  Other options that war could be proposed.  Work with the UN, give peace a chance.  Give democracy a chance.  You never know, it could have worked out properly without anyone, especially from the US, 'dying for the cause'.  What cause again?  Oh, patriotism.
<br />

<br />

<br />
I am totally open to any valid reasoning for the attack on Iraq.  However, thus far, you still have not given me any good reason except for the fact that Saddam was a mean man that did not treat his people properly, and still that is a view that could not be good grounds for any War.  An uprising against its own country?  Now that warrants it.
<br />

<br />
Please, I'd like to hear what you have to say.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Cheers,
<br />

<br />
Darial<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
